Introduction¶

Education is a fundamental human right and a critical driver of personal and societal development. However, despite global progress, millions of children and adolescents remain excluded from the education system. Understanding where and why these gaps exist is crucial for designing effective interventions.

This report explores global patterns in educational access by analyzing out-of-school rates for the year 2020. Using UNICEF data, we examine how economic prosperity (GDP per capita) and regional differences influence the likelihood of children being out of school.

Through five key visualizations, this report highlights global trends, regional disparities, country-specific challenges, and the economic factors affecting education. Together, these insights build a story of progress, inequality, and opportunity in the journey towards universal education.

🚨 Top 10 Countries with Highest Out-of-School Rates (2020)¶

The following bar chart highlights the ten countries with the highest rates of children out of school in 2020, illustrating critical areas for international intervention and support.

The chart also reveals that countries like Senegal, Burkina Faso, and Tuvalu face the highest out-of-school rates, exceeding 60%. Gender disparities are noticeable, with slight variations between male and female rates across countries. These findings highlight urgent educational challenges in specific regions, emphasizing the need for targeted global efforts to ensure inclusive schooling for all children.

import pandas as pd
import plotnine as p9

# Load the dataset
indicator = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Filter for 2020 and drop missing values
df_2020 = indicator[(indicator['time_period'] == 2020) & (indicator['obs_value'].notna())]

# Get top 10 countries by Total rate
top_total = (
    df_2020[df_2020['sex'] == 'Total']
    .sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=False)
    .head(10)
    .copy()
)

# Get all gender data for those countries
top_countries = top_total['country'].tolist()
top10 = df_2020[df_2020['country'].isin(top_countries)].copy()

# Set the country order to match Total ranking
top10['country'] = pd.Categorical(top10['country'], categories=top_total['country'], ordered=True)

# Plot with grouped bars and labels
plot = (
    p9.ggplot(top10, p9.aes(x='country', y='obs_value', fill='sex')) +
    p9.geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', width=0.7) +
    p9.geom_text(
        p9.aes(label='obs_value'),
        position=p9.position_dodge(width=0.7),
        va='bottom',
        size=6,
        format_string='{:.0f}'
    ) +
    p9.labs(
        title='Top 10 Countries with Highest Out-of-School Rates (2020)',
        subtitle='Comparison by Gender – Females, Males, and Overall',
        x='Country',
        y='Out-of-School Rate (%)',
        fill='Gender'
    ) +
    p9.theme_minimal() +
    p9.theme(
        figure_size=(12, 6),
        axis_text_x=p9.element_text(angle=45, hjust=1),
        legend_position='right'
    )
)

plot

📈 Global Trends in School Access (2014–2020)¶

This line chart shows how global access to education has evolved over time. A steady improvement is visible, though gaps persist across regions and gender groups.

The global trend of out-of-school rates between 2014 and 2020 shows significant fluctuations. After peaking around 2017, there was a slight decline by 2018, followed by another rise in 2020. Despite some progress, the overall trend highlights ongoing instability in global school access, suggesting that consistent and sustained efforts are needed to ensure education for all.

# 📈 Global Trend Over Time

# Calculate the world average by year
global_trend = (
    indicator[indicator['sex'] == 'Total']
    .groupby('time_period')['obs_value']
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
)

# Plot the trend
global_trend_plot = (
    p9.ggplot(global_trend, p9.aes(x='time_period', y='obs_value')) +
    p9.geom_line(color="blue") +
    p9.geom_point(color="red") +
    p9.labs(
        title="Global Trend of Out-of-School Rates (2014–2020)",
        x="Year",
        y="Average Out-of-School Rate (%)"
    ) +
    p9.theme(figure_size=(10, 5))
)

🗺️ Regional Differences in Out-of-School Rates (2020)¶

{width=800px}

The regional map reveals stark disparities in school access across the globe in 2020. Sub-Saharan Africa and parts of South Asia show the highest out-of-school rates, indicated by darker blue shades. In contrast, Europe and North America show significantly lower rates. This highlights the urgent need for targeted interventions in regions most affected by educational exclusion.

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Load the UNICEF indicator data
indicator = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Filter for 2020 and 'Total' gender
df_2020 = indicator[
    (indicator['time_period'] == 2020) &
    (indicator['sex'] == 'Total') &
    (indicator['obs_value'].notna())
]

# Create the Choropleth map
fig = px.choropleth(
    df_2020,
    locations="alpha_3_code",        # ISO-3 country codes
    color="obs_value",               # Out-of-school rate
    hover_name="country",            # Hover tooltip shows country name
    color_continuous_scale=px.colors.sequential.Blues,
    title="🌍 Regional Differences in Out-of-School Rates (2020)<br><sup>Higher rates shown in darker blue. Localized interventions needed.</sup>",
    projection="natural earth",      # Globe projection
)

# Update layout for cleaner background
fig.update_layout(
    geo=dict(
        showframe=False,
        showcoastlines=True,
        coastlinecolor="LightGray",
        showland=True,
        landcolor="whitesmoke",
        showocean=True,
        oceancolor="lightblue"
    ),
    margin={"r":0,"t":50,"l":0,"b":0},
    coloraxis_colorbar=dict(
        title="Out-of-School<br>Rate (%)"
    )
)

# Instead of fig.show(), SAVE the figure as image
fig.write_image("/content/regional_differences_map.png", scale=2)

📊 Regional Disparities in Out-of-School Rates (2020)¶

{width=800px}

This bar chart highlights average out-of-school rates across different world regions in 2020.
Regions such as Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia face the steepest challenges, while Europe and East Asia report the lowest rates, showcasing vast inequalities in access to education.

In 2020, South Asia recorded the highest average out-of-school rate at 40%, followed by the "Other" category at 30% and the Middle East & North Africa at 25%. Latin America & the Caribbean had the lowest rate at 10%. This highlights stark regional inequalities, emphasizing that South Asia and parts of Africa require intensified educational investments and policy focus.

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Reload dataset
indicator = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Filter for 2020 and 'Total'
df_2020 = indicator[
    (indicator['time_period'] == 2020) &
    (indicator['sex'] == 'Total') &
    (indicator['obs_value'].notna())
].copy()

# Region mapping
region_mapping = {
    'India': 'South Asia', 'Pakistan': 'South Asia', 'Bangladesh': 'South Asia', 'Nepal': 'South Asia',
    'Nigeria': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Ethiopia': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Kenya': 'Sub-Saharan Africa',
    'South Africa': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Uganda': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Tanzania': 'Sub-Saharan Africa',
    'China': 'East Asia & Pacific', 'Indonesia': 'East Asia & Pacific', 'Philippines': 'East Asia & Pacific',
    'Vietnam': 'East Asia & Pacific', 'Thailand': 'East Asia & Pacific',
    'Brazil': 'Latin America & Caribbean', 'Mexico': 'Latin America & Caribbean', 'Argentina': 'Latin America & Caribbean',
    'Colombia': 'Latin America & Caribbean', 'Peru': 'Latin America & Caribbean',
    'Egypt': 'Middle East & North Africa', 'Morocco': 'Middle East & North Africa', 'Algeria': 'Middle East & North Africa',
    'United Kingdom': 'Europe', 'Germany': 'Europe', 'France': 'Europe', 'Italy': 'Europe', 'Spain': 'Europe',
    'United States': 'North America', 'Canada': 'North America',
}

# Apply mapping safely
df_2020.loc[:, 'region'] = df_2020['country'].map(region_mapping)
df_2020['region'] = df_2020['region'].fillna('Other')

# Group by region
region_grouped = (
    df_2020
    .groupby('region', as_index=False)['obs_value']
    .mean()
)

# Sort by out-of-school rate (ascending)
region_grouped = region_grouped.sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=True)

# Create a horizontal bar chart
fig = px.bar(
    region_grouped,
    x="obs_value",
    y="region",
    title="🌍 Regional Disparities in Out-of-School Rates (2020)",
    color="obs_value",
    color_continuous_scale="Blues",
    text_auto='.2s',
    orientation='h'
)

# Update trace and layout
fig.update_traces(
    textfont_size=14,
    textposition="outside",
    cliponaxis=False,
    marker_line_color='black',
    marker_line_width=1.5
)

fig.update_layout(
    xaxis_title="Average Out-of-School Rate (%)",
    yaxis_title="Region",
    title_font_size=24,
    title_x=0.5,
    font=dict(
        family="Arial",
        size=14,
        color="black"
    ),
    plot_bgcolor='white',
    paper_bgcolor='white',
    coloraxis_showscale=False
)

# Instead of fig.show(), save as a PNG image
fig.write_image("/content/regional_disparities_out_of_school_rates.png", scale=2)

💰 Wealth vs. 📚 Education Access (2020)¶

{width=800px}

This scatter plot illustrates the correlation between a country's GDP per capita and the percentage of children out of school.
We observe that wealthier nations tend to have lower out-of-school rates, whereas low-income countries face more significant educational barriers.
⚠️ Note: Due to limited data availability, the scatter plot includes only a subset of countries for which both education and GDP information were available. Nonetheless, the trend illustrates a general pattern where higher GDP per capita is associated with lower out-of-school rates.

In [6]:
# Step 1: Import libraries
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Step 2: Load datasets
indicator = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")
gdp = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_2.csv")

# Step 3: Filter both datasets for 2020 and 'Total'
df_2020 = indicator[
    (indicator['time_period'] == 2020) &
    (indicator['sex'] == 'Total') &
    (indicator['obs_value'].notna())
].copy()

gdp_data = gdp[
    (gdp['time_period'] == 2020) &
    (gdp['sex'] == 'Total') &
    (gdp['obs_value'].notna())
][['country', 'obs_value']].rename(columns={'obs_value': 'gdp_per_capita'}).copy()

# Step 4: Merge the datasets
merged_data = pd.merge(
    df_2020[['country', 'obs_value']],
    gdp_data,
    how='inner',
    on='country'
)

# Step 5: Add Region Mapping
region_mapping = {
    'India': 'South Asia', 'Pakistan': 'South Asia', 'Bangladesh': 'South Asia', 'Nepal': 'South Asia',
    'Nigeria': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Ethiopia': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Kenya': 'Sub-Saharan Africa',
    'South Africa': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Uganda': 'Sub-Saharan Africa', 'Tanzania': 'Sub-Saharan Africa',
    'China': 'East Asia & Pacific', 'Indonesia': 'East Asia & Pacific', 'Philippines': 'East Asia & Pacific',
    'Vietnam': 'East Asia & Pacific', 'Thailand': 'East Asia & Pacific',
    'Brazil': 'Latin America & Caribbean', 'Mexico': 'Latin America & Caribbean', 'Argentina': 'Latin America & Caribbean',
    'Colombia': 'Latin America & Caribbean', 'Peru': 'Latin America & Caribbean',
    'Egypt': 'Middle East & North Africa', 'Morocco': 'Middle East & North Africa', 'Algeria': 'Middle East & North Africa',
    'United Kingdom': 'Europe', 'Germany': 'Europe', 'France': 'Europe', 'Italy': 'Europe', 'Spain': 'Europe',
    'United States': 'North America', 'Canada': 'North America',
}

merged_data['region'] = merged_data['country'].map(region_mapping)
merged_data['region'] = merged_data['region'].fillna('Other')

# Step 6: Plot the colored scatter plot
fig = px.scatter(
    merged_data,
    x='gdp_per_capita',
    y='obs_value',
    hover_name='country',
    color='region',  # Color by region
    trendline='ols',
    labels={
        'gdp_per_capita': 'GDP per Capita (USD)',
        'obs_value': 'Out-of-School Rate (%)',
        'region': 'Region'
    },
    title="💰 Wealth vs. 📚 Education Access (2020)",
    template="plotly_white",
    color_discrete_sequence=px.colors.qualitative.Set1
)

# Step 7: Beautify layout
fig.update_layout(
    plot_bgcolor='white',
    xaxis=dict(
        showgrid=True,
        gridcolor='lightgrey',
        title_font=dict(size=14),
        tickfont=dict(size=12)
    ),
    yaxis=dict(
        showgrid=True,
        gridcolor='lightgrey',
        title_font=dict(size=14),
        tickfont=dict(size=12)
    ),
    title_font=dict(size=24),
    title_x=0.5,
    font=dict(family="Arial", size=14)
)

# Step 8: 🔥 Save the plot as an image instead of fig.show()
fig.write_image("/content/wealth_vs_education_access.png", scale=2)

Conclusion¶

This analysis of global out-of-school rates in 2020 highlights both progress and persistent inequality in access to education.
While wealthier countries have made remarkable strides towards universal education, many low- and middle-income countries continue to face serious challenges.

Regional differences are stark: Sub-Saharan Africa and parts of South Asia still have alarmingly high out-of-school rates compared to Europe and North America.
Moreover, our scatter plot analysis shows that economic prosperity remains a critical factor in determining educational access.

To achieve universal education goals, the international community must continue investing in infrastructure, targeted policies, and programs that address the barriers to schooling — especially in economically disadvantaged regions.
The path forward requires coordinated global efforts to ensure every child has the opportunity to access quality education, regardless of where they live.

This report also highlights the critical link between economic prosperity and access to education. While some regions have made progress, many countries still face significant barriers to universal schooling. Continued efforts are essential to bridge global education gaps

Reflection and Insights¶

This analysis highlights the deep inequalities that persist in global education access. Wealth disparities, regional differences, and national economic challenges are strongly linked to higher out-of-school rates. Understanding these patterns is critical for shaping effective education policies and targeted interventions. Addressing educational inequality is not just a moral imperative, but also essential for fostering global development, social equity, and long-term economic growth.
